{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17499967","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17499967"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:06:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:06:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1590"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1590","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1590"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.16,0.27,0.37,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1590"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100843"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1590","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1590"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1590"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83268"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"853"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1258"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11195"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16224"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19323"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34643"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37536"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39532"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100843","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/100843"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 89-year-old woman is admitted with gastric outlet obstruction secondary to a stenosing carcinoma of the stomach antrum. She takes no regular medications and has no significant medical history except from a procedure performed 40 years earlier. The type of operation that was performed can be determined from the CT findings (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following procedures was likely performed?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Vagotomy and pyloroplasty","Portacaval shunt","Bilroth I gastrectomy","Choledochoduodenostomy","Left nephrectomy"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe distended stomach full of food material can clearly be seen. The most obvious other abnormality is a gas pattern over the liver. This appearance fits for gas either in the portal venous system or the biliary tree. If this was in the venous system, this would imply sepsis and the patient would be acutely very ill.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe commonest explanation for such a finding in an asymptomatic patient is gas that has arrived in the biliary tree by way of the gut. In other words, the sphincter of Oddi has been rendered incompetent or there is an abnormal communication between the digestive tract and the biliary system. The commonest explanation is previous endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography (ERCP) and sphincterotomy. Probably the next most encountered cause is a post-inflammatory cholecystenterostomy. ie after a bout or bouts of acute cholecystitis, a fistulous communication has developed between the gallbladder and the adjacent small bowel. This is usually the duodenum, with the formation of a \u003Cstrong\u003Echoledochoduodenostomy\u003C/strong\u003E. These patients tend not to develop any complications as a result of this fistula, although a large gallstone could pass and cause small bowel obstruction - the so-called \u0027gallstone ileus.\u0027\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, the patient had a cholecystectomy and choledochoduodenostomy. In the days before ERCP this was a frequently performed operative procedure to deal with common duct stones. None of the other listed procedures would lead to any communication with the biliary tree. The CT slice is to proximal to visualise the kidneys.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Gas in the biliary tree is not usually of any pathological significance."],"references":["Gurusamy KS, Davidson BR. Gallstones. BMJ. 2014;348:g2669. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24755732/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83268"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1590"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15293"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15293","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15293"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ae084437-6b50-4a1c-a095-9c500082a5a0.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ae084437-6b50-4a1c-a095-9c500082a5a0.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":625,"height":491}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83268","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/83268"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-27T08:57:51+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-27T08:58:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1590"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100843"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"7